  "summary": "After a tense exchange where the narrator questions whether Misty’s search for the divine is merely an escape from fear, Misty asks if the narrator is a god. Unable to affirm or deny this, the narrator feels regret for being unable to save her. Misty then decides to go to the church to play Bach.\n\nThe narrator enters a house where Detective Hidewell is tidying up and Detective Tsujimura is frustrated by a lack of leads. Detective McArthur is behaving provocatively, lounging in Wakatsuki's chair and irritating the Chief Inspector. McArthur reveals that he discovered the headless corpses of the twins, Mirei and Kaina, on a ship after a walk by the lake, though he had known about them since after two o'clock. He dismisses the idea that the murders were for inheritance, suggesting the twins were simply in the way.\n\nMcArthur narrows the suspects to Kaji, Kiri, and Yuzu. He notes that Kiri was the only one upstairs during Akiba's murder, which implies Misty could be the killer through process of elimination. The narrator finds this suggestion difficult to accept. As the narrator follows McArthur to understand his intentions, McArthur mocks the detectives' emotional limitations and their tendency to change attitudes once a case is solved. When questioned about his ability to solve the case, McArthur claims he can do what Mutsuzaki cannot and offers the narrator a hint: that their perspective needs to be broader.",
